    <h2>What Makes a Gummy Supplement Vegan?</h2>

    <p>A truly vegan gummy must eliminate every animal-derived component — not just gelatin. The most common animal ingredients hiding in gummy supplements are gelatin (from bovine or porcine collagen), beeswax (used as a glazing agent), carmine (a red pigment from cochineal insects), shellac (secreted by lac insects for coating), and lanolin-derived vitamin D3 (from sheep wool). Vegan gummies replace these with pectin or agar-agar for gelling, carnauba wax for coating, plant-based colorants, and lichen-sourced vitamin D3.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="leaf" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Pectin vs Gelatin</h4>
        <p>Pectin, extracted from citrus peel or apple pomace, creates a softer, slightly less chewy gummy than gelatin. It dissolves at the same rate in stomach acid and has no impact on ingredient bioavailability. Pectin is also more heat-stable, making vegan gummies less prone to melting.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="shield" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Certifications to Trust</h4>
        <p>Look for the Vegan Society trademark, Certified Vegan logo, or PETA-Approved Vegan label. These require full ingredient auditing and supply chain verification. A product labeled "plant-based" without certification may still contain trace animal derivatives.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="flask" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Lichen-Derived Vitamin D3</h4>
        <p>Vegan vitamin D3 from lichen is chemically identical to lanolin-sourced D3 and has equivalent bioavailability. It raises serum 25(OH)D levels just as effectively as animal-derived D3, making it the gold standard for vegan supplementation.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="eye" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Hidden Animal Ingredients</h4>
        <p>Watch for carmine (E120), shellac (confectioner's glaze), beeswax, and "natural flavors" that may include animal derivatives. Even products marketed as "natural" or "plant-based" can contain these hidden non-vegan components.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

