    <!-- NUTRIENTS FOR VEGANS -->
    <h2>Critical Nutrients for Vegans: Why Gummy Supplements Matter</h2>

    <p>Plant-based diets provide excellent nutrition in most areas but create specific gaps that supplementation can fill. The following nutrients are either absent from or poorly absorbed in vegan diets, making targeted supplementation essential for long-term health.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="dna" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Vitamin B12</h4>
        <p>B12 is found only in animal foods and fortified products. Deficiency causes irreversible nerve damage. Every vegan needs a reliable B12 source — gummies providing 500-1000mcg methylcobalamin are ideal for daily compliance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="sun" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Vitamin D3</h4>
        <p>Few foods contain meaningful vitamin D, and vegan sources are even more limited. Lichen-derived D3 gummies at 1000-2000 IU daily maintain optimal serum levels, especially for those living above the 37th parallel with limited sun exposure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="brain" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Omega-3 DHA/EPA</h4>
        <p>ALA from flax and chia converts to DHA/EPA at only 5-10% efficiency. Algal DHA/EPA gummies bypass this limitation entirely, providing the preformed long-chain omega-3s critical for brain and cardiovascular health.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="fitness" size={22} /></div>
        <h4>Creatine</h4>
        <p>Dietary creatine comes exclusively from meat and fish. Vegan baseline creatine stores are 20-30% lower than omnivores, and supplementation improves both physical performance and cognitive function in plant-based populations.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">&#9888;</span>
      <p><strong>Collagen is not vegan.</strong> All collagen supplements are derived from animal sources (bovine, marine, or chicken). Products marketed as "vegan collagen" actually contain collagen-boosting ingredients like vitamin C, silica, and biotin — not collagen itself. If you see "plant-based collagen gummies," understand that you are getting a collagen support formula, not actual collagen protein.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- VERDICT -->
    <div class="verdict">
      <h3>The Bottom Line on Vegan Gummies</h3>
      <p>The vegan gummy supplement market has matured to the point where plant-based consumers face no meaningful compromise on ingredient quality, dosing accuracy, or product variety. Pectin-based formulations deliver equivalent bioavailability to gelatin gummies, and major brands have made the switch across entire product lines. The only categories where vegans face genuine limitations are collagen (no plant-based equivalent exists) and high-dose omega-3 (algal sources are limited in gummy format).</p>
      <p>For a complete vegan supplement stack, we recommend: a vegan multivitamin with B12 and D3, a creatine gummy (especially for athletes), and an algal omega-3 supplement. Add category-specific gummies like melatonin for sleep or ashwagandha for stress management as needed.</p>
    </div>

