    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Vegan Gummies — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What makes a gummy supplement vegan?</summary><p>A vegan gummy replaces gelatin with plant-based gelling agents like pectin or agar-agar and excludes beeswax, carmine, shellac, and animal-sourced active ingredients. Look for Vegan Society, Certified Vegan, or PETA-Approved Vegan certifications.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are vegan gummies as effective as gelatin-based gummies?</summary><p>Yes. The gelling agent has no impact on bioavailability. Pectin gummies dissolve and release nutrients at comparable rates to gelatin gummies. The active compounds are absorbed identically regardless of the delivery matrix.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is vitamin D3 in vegan gummies actually plant-based?</summary><p>Yes — vegan D3 is sourced from lichen, a symbiotic algae-fungus organism. It is chemically identical to lanolin-derived D3 with the same bioavailability and is used by most vegan gummy brands.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do vegan gummies contain more sugar than regular gummies?</summary><p>No significant difference. Vegan gummies contain comparable sugar levels (2-4g per serving). Sugar-free vegan options sweetened with stevia, monk fruit, or allulose are widely available.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What nutrients are hardest to get in vegan gummy form?</summary><p>Collagen (all collagen is animal-derived), omega-3 DHA/EPA (limited in gummy form from algal sources), and iron (metallic taste is difficult to mask). Vegan alternatives use collagen-boosting ingredients or algal omega-3 instead.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are vegan gummies more expensive?</summary><p>Typically 10-25% more due to pectin cost and formulation complexity. The gap has narrowed as demand increased, and many brands now make all gummies vegan by default, eliminating the premium.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How can I verify a gummy is truly vegan?</summary><p>Check for third-party certifications (Vegan Society, Certified Vegan, PETA-Approved). Read the full ingredient list for hidden animal derivatives: gelatin, beeswax, carmine (E120), shellac (confectioner's glaze), and lanolin-derived D3.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do vegan gummies have a shorter shelf life?</summary><p>Comparable shelf life (12-18 months). Pectin is actually more heat-stable than gelatin but slightly more humidity-sensitive. Store in a cool, dry place with the container sealed.</p></details>
    </section>

